05665nam a22011295i 9780691218106DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211993nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912181067 a10.1515/97806912181062doi  a(DE-B1597)567576  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREL0070002bisacsh04a294.3/9272231 aFaure, Bernard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChan Insights and Oversights :bAn Epistemological Critique of the Chan Tradition /cBernard Faure. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (340 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART ONE -- tCHAPTER ONE Chan/Zen in the Western Imagination -- tCHAPTER TWO The Rise of Zen Orientalism -- tCHAPTER THREE Rethinking Chan Historiography -- tCHAPTER FOUR Alternatives -- tPART TWO -- tCHAPTER FIVE Space and Place -- tCHAPTER SIX Times and Tides -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Chan and Language: Fair and Unfair Games -- tCHAPTER EIGHT In-scribing/De-scribing Chan -- tCHAPTER NINE The Paradoxes of Chan Individualism -- tEPILOGUE -- tGLOSSARY -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor many people attracted to Eastern religions (particularly Zen Buddhism), Asia seems the source of all wisdom. As Bernard Faure examines the study of Chan/Zen from the standpoint of postmodern human sciences and literary criticism, he challenges this inversion of traditional "Orientalist" discourse: whether the Other is caricatured or idealized, ethnocentric premises marginalize important parts of Chan thought. Questioning the assumptions of "Easterners" as well, including those of the charismatic D. T. Suzuki, Faure demonstrates how both West and East have come to overlook significant components of a complex and elusive tradition. Throughout the book Faure reveals surprising hidden agendas in the modern enterprise of Chan studies and in Chan itself. After describing how Jesuit missionaries brought Chan to the West, he shows how the prejudices they engendered were influenced by the sectarian constraints of Sino-Japanese discourse. He then assesses structural, hermeneutical, and performative ways of looking at Chan, analyzes the relationship of Chan and local religion, and discusses Chan concepts of temporality, language, writing, and the self. Read alone or with its companion volume, The Rhetoric of Immediacy, this work offers a critical introduction not only to Chinese and Japanese Buddhism but also to "theory" in the human sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHermeneuticsxReligious aspectsxZen Buddhism. 0aKnowledge, Theory of (Buddhism). 0aZen BuddhismxDoctrines. 0aZen BuddhismxStudy and teaching. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh  aAnesaki Masaharu.  aArima Tatsuo.  aBakhtin, Mikhail.  aBenveniste, Emile.  aBodhiruci.  aCaoxi.  aDahui Zonggao.  aDarumashū.  aDōgen Studies.  aEdkins, Joseph.  aFreedman, Maurice.  aFreud, Sigmund.  aGokhale, B. G.  aGuṇabhadra.  aHuayan (Kegon).  aHuihong.  aInoue Hisashi.  aJameson, Fredric.  aJansenists.  aKalupahana, David.  aKegon-Zen.  aLyotard, Jean-François.  aLévi-Strauss, Claude.  aMagliola, Robert.  aMujaku Dōchū.  aNietzsche, Friedrich.  aNukariya Kaiten.  aOng, Walter.  aPuhua.  aSengchou.  aShenhui (Heze),.  aautobiography.  acomparativism.  ahermeneutics.  aideology.  amummies (in Chan).  aobjectivism.  aperformative language.  arhetoric.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 192